  planner_response {
    thinking: "**Defining Deployment Steps**\n\nI\'m focusing on the AWS deployment steps. First, I plan to detail how to dockerize the application. This is the initial stage, laying the groundwork for more complex deployment strategies later. This involves preparing the application for containerization.\n\n\n**Evaluating Deployment Options**\n\nI\'ve been evaluating the optimal deployment method on AWS, leaning toward the most streamlined approach for this application\'s scope. I am now evaluating the possibility of AWS App Runner. For more robust options, I am considering Amazon ECS on Fargate. Detailed steps for setting up VPCs, Security Groups, and ALBs will be provided for either App Runner or Fargate.\n\\n\\n\nAddressing encryption, I want to clarify that all API calls and web telemetry endpoints, specifically `/api/export/csv/*` and `/api/export/json/*`, use HTTPS with TLS 1.2 or 1.3, so Databricks\' data retrieval is encrypted.\n\n\n"
    modified_response: "### AWS Deployment Strategy\n\nBecause your **PulseStream** application uses a full-stack configuration consisting of an **Express.js backend** and a compiled **React SPA frontend** served from a single server instance (`dist/server.cjs`), the most robust production roadmap is to containerize the application and deploy it using a managed container service.\n\nBelow are the architectural steps to deploy your application to **AWS App Runner** (perfect for fully-managed applications) or **AWS ECS Fargate** (suited for enterprise-scale controls).\n\n---\n\n### Step-by-Step Deployment Guide\n\n#### 1. Containerize the Applet\nTo run in AWS managed runtimes, create a standard `Dockerfile` in your root directory:\n\n```dockerfile\n# Build phase\nFROM node:20-alpine AS builder\nWORKDIR /app\nCOPY package*.json ./\nRUN npm ci\nCOPY . .\nRUN npm run build\n\n# Execution phase\nFROM node:20-alpine AS runner\nWORKDIR /app\nENV NODE_ENV=production\nENV PORT=3000\nCOPY package*.json ./\nRUN npm ci --only=production\nCOPY --from=builder /app/dist ./dist\n# If node_modules or dependencies are required for the server start script\nCOPY --from=builder /app/node_modules ./node_modules\n\nEXPOSE 3000\nCMD [\"npm\", \"start\"]\n```\n\n#### 2. Publish to Amazon Elastic Container Registry (ECR)\nUpload the built image to AWS:\n1. Open the ECR Console and create a private repository named `pulsestream-app`.\n2. Authenticate your local Docker daemon with AWS CLI:\n   ```bash\n   aws ecr get-login-password --region <your-region> | docker login --username AWS --password-stdin <aws_account_id>.dkr.ecr.<your-region>.amazonaws.com\n   ```\n3. Build and tag the docker container:\n   ```bash\n   docker build -t pulsestream-app .\n   docker tag pulsestream-app:latest <aws_account_id>.dkr.ecr.<your-region>.amazonaws.com/pulsestream-app:latest\n   ```\n4. Push to AWS:\n   ```bash\n   docker push <aws_account_id>.dkr.ecr.<your-region>.amazonaws.com/pulsestream-app:latest\n   ```\n\n#### 3. Deploy onto AWS App Runner (Recommended for low-ops)\nAWS App Runner automatically provisions hardware, scales, manages SSL certificates, and handles load balancing.\n1. Open the **AWS App Runner Console** and click **Create service**.\n2. Select **Container registry** &rarr; **Amazon ECR**.\n3. Choose your `pulsestream-app` repository and the `latest` tag.\n4. Set the **Deployment trigger** to *Automatic* if you want to redeploy whenever a new image is pushed.\n5. In **Service configuration**, set:\n   - **Port**: `3000` (matches Express listener)\n   - **Environment Variables**: Add your persistent storage credentials or runtime variables (such as `DATABASE_URL` or secret keys).\n6. Complete creation. App Runner will spin up the container and output an HTTPS endpoint.\n\n---\n\n### Encryption Controls: Data In-Transit between AWS & Databricks\n\nWhen transferring demo Protected Health Information (PHI) datasets from your AWS-hosted Express API to your Databricks Workspace (via Spark or HTTPS egress streams), multiple strict encryption boundaries guard the transport:\n\n#### 1. HTTPS / TLS 1.2+ Security Boundaries (Public Endpoint Route)\nWhen Databricks requests records through PySpark via your custom CSV/JSON endpoints (e.g., `/api/export/csv/*` or `/api/export/json/*`):\n- **Transport Encryption**: All requests must traverse an HTTPS endpoint. During AWS App Runner deployment or ALB configuration, AWS automatically provisions a public SSL/TLS certificate utilizing TLS 1.2 or TLS 1.3 custom policies.\n- **Payload Interception Resistance**: This ensures that any clinical data payloads are fully encrypted before leaving your AWS instance, rendering physical network packets unreadable while traversing public internet routers.\n\n#### 2. AWS PrivateLink & VPC Peering (Private Route)\nFor actual production HIPAA environments where public ingestion endpoints are prohibited:\n- **Private Endpoint Integration**: You can establish a private network connection between your Databricks workspace VPC and your application VPC using **AWS PrivateLink** (VPC Endpoints) or **VPC Peering**.\n- **Local Traffic Only**: By configuring your Databricks processing engines to resolve endpoints utilizing private local IP ranges (e.g., in a `10.x.x.x` subnet), the demo PHI datasets flow entirely through dedicated AWS fiber optics without ever exposing route headers or packets to the public internet.\n\n#### 3. Spark Dataframe Native Encryption\nWhen writing the ingested data down to high-performance storage tables on Databricks DBFS or AWS S3 (Silver/Gold stages):\n- **Server-Side Storage Encryption (SSE-S3/SSE-KMS)**: S3 buckets utilized by Databricks run persistent double-envelope encryption at rest using AWS KMS (Key Management Service) standard **AES-256** keys."
    thinking_duration {
      seconds: 2
      nanos: 526628352
    }
    stop_reason: STOP_REASON_STOP_PATTERN
  }
}
